value.value: Distance between the hairline (trichion) and the glabella (the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose), in the midline, more than two SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between the hairline and the glabella.

definition.value: This feature gives the appearance of a short forehead. It is distinct from hirsutism of the forehead. In the latter, orientation of hair growth is lateral and texture and density of hair differs from scalp hair.

value.value: Reduced muscle tone of a muscle that is innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).
Abnormal prominence of the chin related to increased length of the mandible.
A marked tapering of the lower face to the chin.

definition.value: The two rami of the mandible meet at an acute angle.

value.value: A form of developmental hypoplasia of the mandible in which the mandible is mislocalised posteriorly.
The facial appearance is more circular than usual as viewed from the front.
Interpupillary distance more than 2 SD above the mean (alternatively, the appearance of an increased interpupillary distance or widely spaced eyes).
Flat skin surface, with no ridge formation in the central region of the upper lip between the nasal base and upper vermilion border.

definition.value: There is a spectrum of this finding from total absence of the philtral ridges to a some prominence of the ridges. The central groove varies from absent to shallow. Normal values for the frequency of smooth philtrum are available. Grading of the smoothness of the philtrum, used in the assessment of Fetal Alcohol Syndrome, has been developed. This finding is greatly influenced by the facial expression, and care should be taken to evaluate the philtrum when the face is in a neutral position. A smooth philtrum can be associated with a Long philtrum. However, the two findings should be coded separately.

value.value: Facial contours, as viewed from the front, show a broad upper face/cranium and lower face/mandible, creating a square appearance.

Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.
Facial contour, as viewed from the front, triangular in shape, with breadth at the temples and tapering to a narrow chin.

definition.value: Several groups have used the term inverted triangular face to emphasize the fact that the point is facing downwards.

value.value: Abnormally small dimension of the Maxilla. Usually creating a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or resulting in a deficient amount of projection of the base of the nose and lower midface region.
Decreased vertical distance from the vermilion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin.

definition.value: The term "micrognathia" should be used when the chin is both short (vertical dimension) and narrow (horizontal dimension).

value.value: Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently increased distance between the two sides of the forehead.

definition.value: Frontotemporalis is a point lateral to the vertical component of the supraorbital ridge, where there is a hollowing. Spreading caliper tips are placed in the deepest part of that hollow. Note that this term should not be confused with prominent forehead.

value.value: Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or apparently narrow intertemporal region (subjective).

definition.value: A reduced distance between the temporal regions (temples) on each side of the head to one another. Frontotemporalis is a point lateral to the vertical component of the supraorbital ridge, where there is a hollowing. Spreading caliper tips are placed in the deepest part of that hollow.

value.value: Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.
Developmental hypoplasia of the mandible.

definition.value: Mandibular hypoplasia, also known as micrognathia, is a term that describes an abnormally small lower jaw.

value.value: An abnormally increased height of the forehead.
Frontal hairline with bilateral arcs to a low point in the midline of the forehead.

definition.value: The hair may need to be pulled back to recognize this feature. Historically, English widows in the 18th century wore a black hat, triangular in shape, with a point facing forward in the midline.

value.value: An abnormality of the external ear.

A type of abnormal location of the ears in which the position of the ears is characterized by posterior rotation (the superior part of the ears is rotated towards the back of the head, and the inferior part of the ears towards the front).

definition.value: Angle formed by the line perpendicular to the Frankfurt plane and the medial longitudinal axis of the ear (the two most remote points of the ear) greater than two standard deviations above the mean for age.

value.value: An abnormality of the inner ear.

definition.value: Tinnitus is an auditory perception that can be described as the experience of sound, in the ear or in the head, in the absence of external acoustic stimulation.

value.value: An abnormality of the lobule of pinna.
An abnormality of the sensory perception of sound.

definition.value: According to the World Health Organization, deafness refers to the complete loss of hearing ability in one or two ears. Hearing impairment refers to both complete and partial loss of the ability to hear.

value.value: A decreased magnitude of the sensory perception of sound.

definition.value: Hearing loss can be categorized by which part of the auditory system is damaged, as conductive hearing loss, sensorineural hearing loss, and mixed hearing loss. Another axis of classification uses the degree of hearing impairment. The degree of hearing loss is computed by using a three frequency average taken at 500 Hz, 1,000 Hz and 2,000 Hz. The average of these three frequencies is called the Pure Tone Average (PTA). 0-20 dB is considered normal, 21-40 dB mild loss, 41-60 dB moderate loss, 61-70 dB moderately severe loss,71-90 dB severe loss, and greater than 90 dB profound loss. Note that the word deafness is occasionally used to describe partial hearing loss. The World Health Organization uses the word deafness to refer to complete loss of the ability to hear, and hearing impairment to refer to any degree of reduced hearing.

value.value: An abnormality of the nose.

definition.value: This bundled term has been retired. It is preferable to code each feature separately.

value.value: Upper insertion of the ear to the scalp below an imaginary horizontal line drawn between the inner canthi of the eye and extending posteriorly to the ear.
Acute otitis media is a short and generally painful infection of the middle ear.

label.value: Incomplete partition of the cochlea type II

value.value: With incomplete partition II, the cochlea consists of 1.5 turns; the apical and middle cochlea turns are undifferentiated and form a cystic apex. The vestibule is normal while the vestibular aqueduct is always enlarged. Developmental arrest occurs at the seventh week of gestation.

definition.value: The triad of incomplete partition of the cochlea type II, dilation of the vestibule, and an enlarged vestibular aqueduct was previously referred to as a Mondini malformation but this nomenclature is no longer recommended. It is important to note that while reading the related literature, it is often not easy to understand if the authors use the correct terminology, so even in recent studies, the term Mondini should be considered with caution.

value.value: An abnormality of the pinna, which is also referred to as the auricle or external ear.

definition.value: The term 'dysplastic' is no longer accepted as a descriptor for an ear with unusual morphology. Each specific anatomical component of the ear should be described when the ear is thought to be abnormal in appearance.

value.value: A rudimentary tag of skin often containing ear tissue including a core of cartilage and located just anterior to the auricle (outer part of the ear).
Increased thickness of the helix of the ear.
A condition in which the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal. That is, excessive curling of the helix edge, whereby the free edge is parallel to the plane of the ear.

definition.value: This is most often seen in the superior helix where it must be distinguished from a Lop ear (where the usual convexity of the posterior border of the ear is lost). Helix folding is highly variable.

value.value: A form of sensorineural deafness with either congenital onset or infantile onset, i.e., before the acquisition of speech.

Median longitudinal ear length greater than two standard deviations above the mean and median ear width greater than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparent increase in length and width of the pinna (subjective).

definition.value: This is acknowledged to be a bundled term but retained here because of its usefulness in practice. Ear length is determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear. If only length is increased the term Long ear should be used.

label.value: Stenosis of the external auditory canal

value.value: An abnormal narrowing of the external auditory canal.
An abnormality of vibrational conductance of sound to the inner ear leading to impairment of sensory perception of sound.

definition.value: A conductive hearing impariment with greater than 90 dB loss.

value.value: A type of hearing impairment in one or both ears related to an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve.

definition.value: Hearing loss caused by damage or dysfunction of the auditory nerve (cranial nerve VIII, also known as the cochlear nerve).

value.value: A progressive form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
A type of hearing loss resulting from a combination of conductive hearing impairment and sensorineural hearing impairment.

Angle formed by the plane of the ear and the mastoid bone greater than the 97th centile for age (objective); or, outer edge of the helix more than 2 cm from the mastoid at the point of maximum distance (objective).

label.value: Atresia of the external auditory canal

value.value: Absence or failure to form of the external auditory canal.
Increased volume and globular shape of the anteroinferior aspect of the nose.

definition.value: This is a bundled term, but as it is useful in practice it is kept here. This alteration of size and shape may be limited to the tip, but may involve the lower third of the nose. If only the width of the nasal tip is increased this should be coded as Broad nasal tip.

value.value: Anterior positioning of the nasal root in comparison to the usual positioning for age.

definition.value: A prominent nasal bridge can occur irrespective of the width of the nasal bridge, and the width should be assessed separately. The nasal bridge becomes more prominent with age. Although the nasal root may be anteriorly placed without increasing the space between the eyes, prominence of the nasal bridge may be accompanied by Telecanthus or ocular Hypertelorism. If such findings are present these should be coded separately. Deep-set eyes may lead to the impression of a prominent nasal bridge, but this finding should be coded separately.

value.value: Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi.

definition.value: The alae nasi are the lateral portions of the nose or the wings of the nostrils, which partly encircle the nostrils (nares). They are usually about the width of the columella, but vary greatly depending on the shape of the nostril. Note that individuals may be described as having a Cleft ala nasi, but have a severely underdeveloped ala nasi. In an underdeveloped ala the continuity of the tissue encircling the nostril is undisturbed while in a cleft it is disrupted. With severe hypoplasia of the nasal alae, the nasal tip may appear depressed.

value.value: Increased breadth of the nasal bridge (and with it, the nasal root).

definition.value: Care should be taken to distinguish between increased width of bone and Fullness of paranasal tissue. A wide nasal bridge should be distinguished from Telecanthus and Hypertelorism. A wide nasal bridge can be either prominent or depressed, which should be coded separately.

value.value: Nasal ridge curving anteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip. The nose appears often also prominent, and the columella low.
Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae.
